multibranch-build-strategy-extension.title: Pipeline: Multibranch build strategy extension
multibranch-build-strategy-extension.excerpt:
This plugin provides additional configuration to prevent multibranch projects from triggering new builds based on a include or exclude regions in source repository or existence of a specific phrase in commit message of latest added commit.
Each region uses ant pattern matching, and must be separated by a new line. Any commented line should start by #
Each message uses Java pattern matching based on standard java.util.regex package, and must be separated by a new line. Examples:
  • Exclusion (Region) # excluding html and jpeg changes to trigger builds src/main/web/**/*.html src/main/web/**/*.jpeg
  • Inclusion (Region) # Any changes on java files will trigger build src/main/java/**/*.java
  • Exclusion (Message) .*\[ci\-skip\].* .*\[maven\-release\-plugin\].*

cloudbees-rbac-auto-configurer.excerpt:
CloudBees RBAC Auto Configurer is capable of automatically creating, when a user logs in, one secured folder matching his username and one secured folder per group this user belongs to.
The security pattern is that the folder matching the username is by default only visible by the user himself and that the folder matching groups are only visible by the members of the group. These security configurations can be modified once the folder is created.
This Auto Configurer plugin requires that the authorization mode of Jenkins is set to 'Role-based matrix authorization strategy'.
For more details on RBAC configuration, see CloudBees Jenkins Enterprise User Guide / Chapter 8. Role Based Access Control Plugin

cloudbees-ci-catalog.name: cloudbees-ci-catalog
cloudbees-ci-catalog.title: CloudBees CI Catalog Plugin
cloudbees-ci-catalog.excerpt:
The CloudBees CI Catalog plugin is designed to simplify data collection and analysis to better manage CI environments. It has two main purposes:
  1. Collect and Analyze Configuration Data: The plugin collects configuration information about your controller and sends it to a CloudBees server, generating a comprehensive report for review with CloudBees support or professional services. This process provides valuable insights into what is running in the CI environment.
  2. Compatibility Check for Jenkins as a Service: Analyze your controller for compatibility with Jenkins® as a Service by CloudBees, identifying incompatible plugins, required agents, and necessary libraries, and generating a comprehensive compatibility report to ensure a smooth migration.
By leveraging the CloudBees CI Catalog plugin, users can achieve greater clarity and control over their CI environments, enabling efficient management and smooth migrations.
